<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Glochidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Glochidion rubrum" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Glochidion rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded widely from India to Cambodia, China, south Japan, Malaysia, Indonesia, Philippines and Vietnam. In China, it occurs in Anhui, Fujian, Guangdong, Hainan, Hong Kong, Taiwan and Zhenjiang. It grows in broad-leaved evergreen forests, roadsides from low altitude to 1800 m. The species is widely distributed from northern to southern Taiwan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="taxonomic discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Taxonomic discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<bibRefCitation author="Hayata, B" journalOrPublisher="Taipei" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="94 - 97" refId="B17" refString="Hayata, B, 1920. Icones Plantarum Formosanarum Bureau Productive Industris. Taipei 9: 94 - 97" title="Icones Plantarum Formosanarum Bureau Productive Industris." volume="9" year="1920">Hayata (1920)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. chademenosocarpum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="chademenosocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. chademenosocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on one of his collections (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">B. Hayata s.n.</emphasis>
, TI, photo!; Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A holotype of Glochidion assamicum var. magnicapsulum Croiatz &amp; Hara (A. Henry 117, A) B holotype of G. kusukusense Hayata (B. Hayata &amp; S. Sasaki s. n., TI) C lectotype of G. lanceolatum Hayata (T. Makino s. n., TI) D holotype of G. chademenosocarpum Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI) E isotype of G. rubrum Blume (C. L. von Blume s. n., NY) F isolectotype of G. suishaense Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.54839.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/449558" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">1D</figureCitation>
) from Taiwan, and he suggested that the species differed from 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(recorded as 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. fortunei" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="fortunei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. fortunei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his study) by its much more densely clustered and sessile female flowers. After checking the protologue and observing the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. chademenosocarpum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="chademenosocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. chademenosocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A holotype of Glochidion assamicum var. magnicapsulum Croiatz &amp; Hara (A. Henry 117, A) B holotype of G. kusukusense Hayata (B. Hayata &amp; S. Sasaki s. n., TI) C lectotype of G. lanceolatum Hayata (T. Makino s. n., TI) D holotype of G. chademenosocarpum Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI) E isotype of G. rubrum Blume (C. L. von Blume s. n., NY) F isolectotype of G. suishaense Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.54839.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/449558" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">1D</figureCitation>
), it was concluded that the species is well conspecific with 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A holotype of Glochidion assamicum var. magnicapsulum Croiatz &amp; Hara (A. Henry 117, A) B holotype of G. kusukusense Hayata (B. Hayata &amp; S. Sasaki s. n., TI) C lectotype of G. lanceolatum Hayata (T. Makino s. n., TI) D holotype of G. chademenosocarpum Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI) E isotype of G. rubrum Blume (C. L. von Blume s. n., NY) F isolectotype of G. suishaense Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.54839.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/449558" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">1E</figureCitation>
) and should be treated as a new synonym of the latter. Based on morphological description (
<bibRefCitation author="Hayata, B" journalOrPublisher="Taipei" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="94 - 97" refId="B17" refString="Hayata, B, 1920. Icones Plantarum Formosanarum Bureau Productive Industris. Taipei 9: 94 - 97" title="Icones Plantarum Formosanarum Bureau Productive Industris." volume="9" year="1920">Hayata 1920</bibRefCitation>
) as well as our observation of the type, we found that the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. chademenosocarpum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="chademenosocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. chademenosocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might represent an unripe flower branch of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the morphology of branch, leaves, ovaries and styles observed are all identical with those of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except the ovaries and styles are smaller in size compared with those of the ripe female flowers described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hsu, YS" journalOrPublisher="Quarterly Journal of Forest Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="49 - 68" refId="B20" refString="Hsu, YS, Lu, FY, Deng, SL, Liaw, JC, 2006. A taxonomic study of the Glochidion (Euphorbiaceae) of Taiwan. Quarterly Journal of Forest Research 28: 49 - 68" title="A taxonomic study of the Glochidion (Euphorbiaceae) of Taiwan." volume="28" year="2006">Hsu et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
as well as those observed in living plants. Additionally, most male flowers observed from the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. chademenosocarpum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="chademenosocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. chademenosocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also seem to be unripe because sepals of most male flowers were unopen (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A holotype of Glochidion assamicum var. magnicapsulum Croiatz &amp; Hara (A. Henry 117, A) B holotype of G. kusukusense Hayata (B. Hayata &amp; S. Sasaki s. n., TI) C lectotype of G. lanceolatum Hayata (T. Makino s. n., TI) D holotype of G. chademenosocarpum Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI) E isotype of G. rubrum Blume (C. L. von Blume s. n., NY) F isolectotype of G. suishaense Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.54839.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/449558" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">1D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
The taxonomic history of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. suishaense" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="suishaense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. suishaense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was similar to that of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. chademenosocarpum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="chademenosocarpum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. chademenosocarpum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. kusukusense" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="kusukusense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. kusukusense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except 
<bibRefCitation author="Hsu, YS" journalOrPublisher="Quarterly Journal of Forest Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" pagination="49 - 68" refId="B20" refString="Hsu, YS, Lu, FY, Deng, SL, Liaw, JC, 2006. A taxonomic study of the Glochidion (Euphorbiaceae) of Taiwan. Quarterly Journal of Forest Research 28: 49 - 68" title="A taxonomic study of the Glochidion (Euphorbiaceae) of Taiwan." volume="28" year="2006">Hsu et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
treated it as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on its protologue. In the present study, the result from observing the type of 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. suishaense" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="suishaense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. suishaense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A holotype of Glochidion assamicum var. magnicapsulum Croiatz &amp; Hara (A. Henry 117, A) B holotype of G. kusukusense Hayata (B. Hayata &amp; S. Sasaki s. n., TI) C lectotype of G. lanceolatum Hayata (T. Makino s. n., TI) D holotype of G. chademenosocarpum Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI) E isotype of G. rubrum Blume (C. L. von Blume s. n., NY) F isolectotype of G. suishaense Hayata (B. Hayata s. n., TI)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.54839.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/449558" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">1F</figureCitation>
) further confirmed its taxonomic status.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. rubrum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="rubrum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">G. rubrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be distinguished from all other Taiwanese 
